  "text": "## Kubernetes Leader Election (Lease-Based)\n\nKubernetes uses a **lease-based leader election** mechanism implemented through the `k8s.io/client-go` library. The core implementation is found in `staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/` with three primary components:\n\n### Architecture\n\n1. **LeaderElector** (leaderelection.go:188-206): The main controller managing the election lifecycle. It maintains state about:\n   - Current observed leader election record\n   - The timestamp when the record was observed\n   - Whether this instance is the leader\n\n2. **Resource Lock Interface** (resourcelock/interface.go:81-100): An abstraction over the underlying storage mechanism. The interface defines:\n   - `Get()`: Retrieve current leader election record\n   - `Create()`: Create a new record if none exists\n   - `Update()`: Update the record with new lease information\n   - `RecordEvent()`: Log events for observability\n\n3. **LeaseLock** (resourcelock/leaselock.go:31-39): The concrete implementation using Kubernetes Lease objects (coordination.k8s.io/v1) to store:\n   - HolderIdentity: The identity of the current leader\n   - LeaseDurationSeconds: How long the lease is valid\n   - RenewTime: When the current holder last renewed\n   - AcquireTime: When leadership was originally acquired\n\n### Election Flow\n\nThe election process follows this call chain:\n\n1. **Run()** (line 211-221): Main entry point that orchestrates the election\n2. **acquire()** (line 252-276): Attempts to become leader by repeatedly calling tryAcquireOrRenew until successful\n3. **tryAcquireOrRenew()** (line 432-503): Core logic that:\n   - For current leader: Updates RenewTime in the lease (fast path)\n   - For candidates: Checks if lease has expired via isLeaseValid()\n   - Creates/updates the lease record\n4. **renew()** (line 279-312): Continuously renews the lease while leader, polling every RetryPeriod within the RenewDeadline\n\n### Failover & Re-election Mechanism\n\nFailover is implicit in the lease expiration mechanism:\n\n1. **Lease Timeout Detection** (line 536-542): The isLeaseValid() function checks if current_time > observedTime + LeaseDurationSeconds. This is calculated locally using the observer's clock without relying on server timestamps.\n\n2. **Re-election Trigger** (line 480-483): When a non-leader candidate observes that a lease has expired:\n   - The lease is no longer valid (current time exceeds RenewTime + LeaseDurationSeconds)\n   - Any candidate can then attempt to acquire the lease\n\n3. **Leader Loss Detection**: If the current leader fails to renew within RenewDeadline (default 10s), it stops leading. Other candidates start trying to acquire the lease immediately.\n\n4. **Failover Time**: Determined by LeaseDuration (default 15s). When a leader fails:\n   - Other candidates wait for the lease to expire (15s)\n   - First candidate to successfully update the lease becomes new leader\n   - Total failover time is roughly LeaseDuration\n\n## etcd Leader Election (Raft-Based)\n\netcd uses the **Raft consensus algorithm** for leader election, implemented through integration with the `go.etcd.io/raft/v3` library. The core implementation is in `server/etcdserver/raft.go` and `server/etcdserver/server.go`.\n\n### Architecture\n\n1. **raftNode** (raft.go:80-104): Wraps the Raft node with:\n   - Message channels for communication (msgSnapC, applyc, readStateC)\n   - Heartbeat ticker for election timeout management\n   - Contention detector to monitor leader health\n\n2. **raftReadyHandler** (server.go, line ~250-280): Handles Raft state changes:\n   - `updateLead()`: Updates who the current leader is\n   - `updateLeadership()`: Reacts to leadership changes (demotes followers, pauses compaction)\n   - `getLead()`: Returns current leader identity\n\n3. **Raft Integration in raftNode.start()** (raft.go:173-306): The main event loop processing Raft protocol messages\n\n### Election Flow\n\nThe Raft-based election process:\n\n1. **start()** (raft.go:173-306): Main goroutine that:\n   - Ticks the Raft state machine periodically (heartbeat interval)\n   - Monitors Ready() channel for state changes\n\n2. **tick()** (raft.go:158-163): Called on each heartbeat interval, advances Raft's internal election timer\n\n3. **Leader Detection** (raft.go:185-197): When Ready() returns with rd.SoftState:\n   - Checks if `rd.SoftState.Lead` indicates a new leader\n   - Updates lead status via `updateLead(rd.SoftState.Lead)`\n   - Sets `islead` flag based on `rd.RaftState == raft.StateLeader`\n\n4. **Message Processing**:\n   - Leader: Sends messages immediately (line 240)\n   - Followers: Process messages after applying (line 297)\n\n### Failover & Re-election Mechanism\n\nFailover in Raft is automatic and consensus-driven:\n\n1. **Heartbeat Monitoring**: The leader sends heartbeats to all followers at regular intervals. Followers maintain an election timeout.\n\n2. **Timeout Detection**: When a follower doesn't receive a heartbeat within the election timeout:\n   - It becomes a candidate\n   - Increments its term\n   - Requests votes from other nodes\n\n3. **Leader Election**: A candidate becomes leader when:\n   - It receives votes from a majority of the cluster\n   - It has the most up-to-date log\n   - This guarantees only one leader per term\n\n4. **Failover Time**: Determined by election timeout (typically 150-300ms in etcd):\n   - Faster than Kubernetes lease-based election (~15s)\n   - Can tolerate network partitions better through quorum-based decisions\n   - Guarantees safety: split-brain is impossible (only one leader can be elected per term)\n\n### Key Differences\n\n1. **Consistency Model**:\n   - Kubernetes: Lease-based, relies on API server lock semantics, vulnerable to clock skew\n   - etcd: Consensus-based through Raft, guarantees strong consistency\n\n2. **Failure Detection**:\n   - Kubernetes: Time-based (lease expiration), takes 15+ seconds\n   - etcd: Heartbeat-based, takes 150-300ms\n\n3. **Split-brain Prevention**:\n   - Kubernetes: Not guaranteed (multiple leaders possible during network partitions)\n   - etcd: Prevented by Raft quorum requirement (only majority can elect leader)\n\n4. **Failover Mechanism**:\n   - Kubernetes: Implicit in lease renewal, candidates wait for lease expiration\n   - etcd: Explicit in Raft protocol, automatic election triggered by timeout\n\n5. **Usage Context**:\n   - Kubernetes: Used by controllers/operators for coordination\n   - etcd: Used for server-to-server leader election within the distributed system itself"
}

